description:
Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) rely on long-chain reasoning (CoT) to improve performance in complex tasks, but existing methods often treat the reasoning process as a sequence generation problem, neglecting the combinatorial gain structure between reasoning steps. In this paper, we propose a novel training and tuning paradigm: Supermodular Reasoning Optimization (SRO). This method introduces supermodular function optimization theory into reasoning trajectory modeling for the first time, treating the set of reasoning steps as a combinatorial system with "marginally increasing gain," thus transforming LRM training into a structured scalar function optimization problem.  
 &nbsp; 
  We define the reasoning gain function as a supermodular scalar function and construct a reasoning selection mechanism based on marginal gain acceleration, enabling the model to automatically learn "when to expand reasoning" and "when to stop reasoning." Simultaneously, we propose a continuously relaxed form of differentiable supermodular optimization objective, allowing it to be embedded into the standard Transformer training process for end-to-end optimization.

